International-English--human-mind-language
senso-concept-Mcs (EnglLago)

McsHitp-creation:: {2019-08-06},

overview of EnglLago

description::
· English-language is an-oral and alphabetic lagHmnm which also is today-{2019} a-common-language.
===
"International English is the concept of the English language as a global means of communication in numerous dialects, and the movement towards an international standard for the language. It is also referred to as Global English, World English, Common English, Continental English, General English, Engas (English as associate language), or Globish. Sometimes, these terms refer simply to the array of varieties of English spoken throughout the world.
Sometimes, "international English" and the related terms above refer to a desired standardisation, i.e., Standard English; however, there is no consensus on the path to this goal. There have-been-many proposals for making International English more accessible to people from different nationalities. Basic English is an example, but it failed to make progress. More recently, there have-been-proposals for English as a lingua franca (ELF) in which non-native speakers take a highly active role in the development of the language. It has also been argued that International English is held back by its traditional spelling. There has been slow progress in adopting alternate spellings."
[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_English{2019-08-09}]

"The number of speech sounds in English varies from dialect to dialect, and any actual tally depends greatly on the interpretation of the researcher doing the counting. The Longman Pronunciation Dictionary by John C. Wells, for example, using symbols of the International Phonetic Alphabet, denotes 24 consonants and 23 vowels used in Received Pronunciation, plus two additional consonants and four additional vowels used in foreign words only. For Generic American it provides for 25 consonants and 19 vowels, with one additional consonant and three additional vowels for foreign words. The American Heritage Dictionary, on the other hand, suggests 25 consonants and 18 vowels (including r-colored vowels) for American English, plus one consonant and five vowels for non-English terms".
[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/English_phonology {2008-04-14}]

EnglPhnm.vowel of speech

description::
· vowel of EnglLago is a-phoneme without airstream-obstruction.

* 2-vowel-word: 1st vowel sounds as in alphabet (long), second silent.
· bake, these, pie, drone, cute.
* 1-vowel-word: short a, e, i, o, u:
· had, bed, him, hot, sum.
[{2025-03-06 retrieved} https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eub0Q2KzV-I]

"Accent Variation: Pronunciation of vowels varies greatly across English accents. For example, the /ɒ/ vowel (LOT) might merge with /ʌ/ (STRUT) or /ɑː/ (START) in some accents. Similarly, diphthongs can be realized differently or become monophthongal.
Spelling is Not Phonetic: English spelling is historical and doesn't perfectly map to current pronunciation. This is why one phoneme can have many spellings and one spelling can represent multiple phonemes.
Stress: Vowel sounds can change depending on whether they are in stressed or unstressed syllables (e.g., the schwa /ə/ is very common in unstressed positions).
Rhotic vs. Non-rhotic: Whether the /r/ sound is pronounced after vowels (rhoticity) affects the realization of vowels like /ɜː/ and the diphthongs /ɪə, eə, ʊə/."
[{2025-03-06 retrieved} https://gemini.google.com/app/6f7b6a8acc038ccb]

description::

· /ʌ/ipa:
· /ə/ipa:
· luck/lak/, cup, sun,
· letters: u, o.

"/ʌ/ (STRUT vowel) - Short, mid central unrounded vowel
Common Letters: u, o, ou, oe, oo (sometimes)
Examples: strut, son, rough, does, blood

/ə/ (SCHWA vowel) - Short, mid central unrounded vowel (very common in unstressed syllables)
Common Letters: a, e, i, o, u, and many vowel digraphs in unstressed syllables (like ar, or, er, our)
Examples: about, taken, pencil, memory, supply, dollar, doctor, father, colour"

phonemes of word

description::
× Mcsh-creation: {2025-11-11},
">js code mapping english words to phonemes:
To map English words to phonemes in JavaScript, one of the most straightforward and accurate approaches is to use the `phonemize` library (a pure JS implementation with rule-based grapheme-to-phoneme conversion, supporting IPA and ARPABET formats). It handles dictionary lookups for common words, rule-based prediction for unknowns, and extras like abbreviation/number expansion.
### Installation
Run this in your project directory:
```
npm install phonemize
```
### Basic Usage Examples
Here's complete, runnable JS code snippets. These assume Node.js (or a bundler like Webpack for browser use).
#### Example 1: Convert a Single Word to IPA Phonemes
```javascript
const { phonemize } = require('phonemize');
// Convert "hello" to IPA phonemes (with stress markers)
console.log(phonemize('hello'));
// Output: həˈɫoʊ
// As an array of phonemes (one per word)
console.log(phonemize('hello', { returnArray: true }));
// Output: ['həˈɫoʊ']
```
#### Example 2: Convert a Sentence to ARPABET Phonemes
```javascript
const { toARPABET } = require('phonemize');
// ARPABET format (common for speech synthesis, with stress numbers 0=unstressed, 1=primary, 2=secondary)
console.log(toARPABET('The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog.'));
// Output: DH AX0 K W IH1 K B R AW1 N F AA1 K S JH AH1 M P S OW1 V ER0 DH AX0 L EY1 Z IY0 D AA1 G .
```
#### Example 3: Custom Options (Strip Stress, Custom Separator, Handle Unknown Words)
```javascript
const { phonemize, addPronunciation } = require('phonemize');
// Add a custom pronunciation for an unknown word
addPronunciation('synagonism', 'sɪˈnæɡənɪzəm'); // Example phonetic mapping
// Convert with options: strip stress, use '-' as separator, return array
const result = phonemize('Synagonism is a cool word!', {
returnArray: true,
stripStress: true,
separator: '-'
});
console.log(result);
// Output: ['sɪ-næ-ɡə-nɪ-zəm', 'ɪ-z', 'ə', 'k-u-l', 'w-ɜɹ-d']
```
#### Example 4: Advanced Tokenization (Get Phonemes with Word Metadata)
```javascript
const { createTokenizer } = require('phonemize');
// Create a custom tokenizer
const tokenizer = createTokenizer({
format: 'ipa', // Or 'arpabet'
stripStress: false, // Keep stress markers
separator: ' ' // Space-separated phonemes per word
});
// Tokenize and get detailed output
const tokens = tokenizer.tokenizeToTokens('Hello, world!');
tokens.forEach(token => {
console.log(`${token.word} -> ${token.phoneme} (at position ${token.position})`);
});
// Output:
// Hello -> həˈɫoʊ (at position 0)
// , -> , (at position 5)
// world -> ˈwɝɫd (at position 7)
// ! -> ! (at position 13)
```
This library processes over 10,000 words per second and covers 125,000+ English words via dictionary. For edge cases (e.g., proper nouns), add custom pronunciations as shown. If you need a dependency-free rule-based implementation (less accurate), let me know for a basic scanner based on NRL rules!"
[{2025-11-10 retrieved} https://x.com/i/grok?conversation=1988141851530887391]

onset of EnglSylb

description::
× Mcsh-creation: {2025-11-10},

* C: 65% Single-consonant onsets (C) are by far the most common,
· Across positional segment-frequency work (phonotactic probability) based on large lexica, the most frequent single onsets belong to a familiar set: /s, t, p, k, b, d, f, m, n, r, l, w, h, g, j/. Exact ranks shift by corpus and phonemic inventory used, but these consistently sit at the top.

* Ø: 22% no-onset (Ø) also occurs,

* CC: 12% two-consonant (CC) onsets are much less common,
· Stop + liquid: /pr, br, tr, dr, kr, gr, pl, bl, kl, gl/ — collectively among the most frequent CC onsets. Wikipedia
· Fricative + liquid: /fl, fr/ — also very common. Wikipedia
· S + stop: /sp, st, sk/ — very common; they also seed most CCC onsets (see below). Wikipedia
· S + sonorant: /sl, sm, sn, sw/ — frequent but a bit below the families above. Wikipedia
· Stop + /w/ (labial/velar): /tw, dw, kw, gw/ — attested, generally less frequent than stop+liquid. Wikipedia

* CCC: 1% three-consonant (CCC) onsets are rare,
· For three-consonant (CCC) onsets, English is extremely restricted: they’re almost always /s/ + (p,t,k) + (l,r,w,j/ “y”). The most frequent CCC members are /str, spr, spl, skr, skw/, with /str/ typically the standout.

syllabication of EnglSylb

description::
"Due to the very weak correspondence between sounds and letters in the spelling of modern English, for example, written syllabification in English has to be based mostly on etymological i.e. morphological instead of phonetic principles. English written syllables therefore do not correspond to the actually spoken syllables of the living language."
[{2019-08-10} https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syllable#Syllabification]
===
· I use a-simple rule: a-text-syllable ends in vowel (aeiou y), except of a-last-syllable which may end and in a-consonant.
· a-syllable has one vowel.
- pho-ne-tic,
- wri-tten,
- vo-wel,
- sy-lla-ble,
- ye-ar,
- o-hi-o-ans,

"### English Noun Plural Formation
English plural formation follows mostly regular patterns, but there are exceptions due to historical, phonetic, and borrowed influences. Below is a summary of the main rules, organized in a table for clarity. Note that pronunciation often guides spelling (e.g., adding -es for an extra syllable).
| Rule Category | Description | Examples |
|---------------|-------------|----------|
| **Regular: Add -s** | Most nouns simply add -s. | cat → cats
dog → dogs
book → books |
| **Add -es (for sibilants)** | Nouns ending in -s, -ss, -sh, -ch, -x, or -z add -es to ease pronunciation. | bus → buses
kiss → kisses
brush → brushes
church → churches
box → boxes
quiz → quizzes |
| **Consonant + y → ies** | Nouns ending in a consonant followed by -y change -y to -ies. | baby → babies
city → cities
fly → flies |
| **Vowel + y → s** | Nouns ending in a vowel followed by -y just add -s. | boy → boys
key → keys
toy → toys |
| **-f/-fe → -ves** | Many nouns ending in -f or -fe change to -ves (though some just add -s). | leaf → leaves
knife → knives
wife → wives

*Exceptions:* roof → roofs
chief → chiefs |
| **-o ending** | Nouns ending in -o often add -es (especially after a vowel or in certain words); others add -s. | potato → potatoes
hero → heroes
tomato → tomatoes

*Add -s:* piano → pianos
photo → photos |
| **Irregular plurals** | Completely change form (often from Old English roots). Common ones: | child → children
man → men
woman → women
foot → feet
tooth → teeth
mouse → mice
goose → geese
louse → lice
ox → oxen |
| **No change (invariable)** | Some nouns stay the same in plural. | sheep → sheep
deer → deer
fish → fish (or fishes for types)
species → species |
| **Foreign/borrowed plurals** | Retain original plural forms from Latin, Greek, etc. (though anglicized forms are common). | datum → data
criterion → criteria
focus → foci (or focuses)
analysis → analyses
crisis → crises
phenomenon → phenomena |
| **Plural-only nouns** | Always plural; no singular form. | scissors
trousers
glasses
news (treated as singular in meaning) |
| **Compound nouns** | Pluralize the main noun; hyphenated forms keep hyphens. | mother-in-law → mothers-in-law
passerby → passersby
commander-in-chief → commanders-in-chief |
#### Additional Notes
- **Mass nouns**: Uncountable nouns like *water*, *information*, or *furniture* don't form plurals (use quantifiers like "some water" instead).
- **Acronyms/Abbreviations**: Usually add -s (e.g., CD → CDs), but add 's if ending in s (e.g., SOS → SOS's).
- **Pronunciation tip**: The -s/-es ending is pronounced /s/ after voiceless sounds (e.g., cats /kæts/), /z/ after voiced sounds (e.g., dogs /dɒɡz/), and /ɪz/ after sibilants (e.g., buses /ˈbʌsɪz/).
- For edge cases or proper nouns, consult a dictionary—English evolves, so exceptions abound (e.g., "octopus" can be octopuses, octopi, or octopodes).
If you have a specific noun or category in mind, provide more details for tailored examples!"

">do you have a complete list of them?
### Is There a Complete List of English Irregular Nouns?
No, there isn't a truly "complete" list of irregular nouns in English because the language is dynamic, with ongoing borrowings from other languages (e.g., Latin, Greek) and regional variations. What counts as "irregular" can also depend on context—some plurals follow patterns that were once standard but now seem exceptional (like -ies for words ending in -y). However, linguists and dictionaries identify a core set of irregularities based on historical patterns from Old English and foreign influences.
Based on authoritative sources like Wiktionary and comprehensive compilations, I've expanded my previous list into a more exhaustive one below. This covers the most commonly recognized irregular plurals, categorized for clarity. It includes over 100 examples, focusing on those that:
- Change vowels (umlaut).
- Add -en or similar.
- Stay the same.
- Use foreign-style endings.
- Have suppletive (totally different) forms.
- Or follow other non-standard rules.
I've prioritized truly irregular ones over semi-regular (e.g., excluding most -y to -ies like "baby → babies," as they're predictable). For daily use, this covers nearly everything you'll encounter.
### 1. **Vowel Changes (Umlaut)**
These shift the internal vowel, a remnant of Old English.
| Singular | Plural | Notes |
|----------|--------|-------|
| foot | feet | Also for units of measurement (e.g., "12 foot"). |
| goose | geese | But "mongoose → mongooses" (regular). |
| louse | lice | Applies to compounds like "woodlouse → woodlice." |
| man | men | For compounds like "postman → postmen" (but "human → humans"). |
| mouse | mice | Computer "mouse → mice" or sometimes "mouses." Applies to "dormouse → dormice." |
| tooth | teeth | For compounds like "eyetooth → eyeteeth." |
| woman | women | For compounds like "policewoman → policewomen." |
### 2. **Add -en or -ren (Weak Nouns)**
Old English endings, now rare.
| Singular | Plural | Notes |
|----------|--------|-------|
| child | children | For compounds like "schoolchild → schoolchildren." |
| ox | oxen | For compounds like "musk-ox → musk-oxen." |
| brother | brethren | Archaic/formal; "brothers" is common today. |
### 3. **Suppletive Forms**
Completely different roots for plural.
| Singular | Plural | Notes |
|----------|--------|-------|
| person | people | Formal: "persons." Compounds like "chairperson → chairpeople." "People" can also be singular for a group. |
### 4. **No Change (Same in Singular and Plural)**
Context (e.g., articles) indicates number.
| Form | Examples/Notes |
|----------|----------------|
| sheep | One sheep, a flock of sheep. |
| deer | One deer, many deer (or "deers" rarely). |
| fish | One fish, many fish; "fishes" for species. |
| moose | One moose, many moose. |
| swine | One swine, many swine (archaic). |
| aircraft | One aircraft, many aircraft. |
| hovercraft | One hovercraft, many hovercraft. |
| spacecraft | One spacecraft, many spacecraft. |
| species | One species, many species. |
| series | One series, many series. |
| Swiss | One Swiss, many Swiss (nationality). |
### 5. **Devoiced or Altered Endings**
Slight twists on regular -s, often from history.
| Singular | Plural | Notes |
|----------|--------|-------|
| die | dice | For gaming cubes; "dies" for tools. |
| penny | pence | British for money amounts; "pennies" for coins. |
### 6. **Foreign Borrowings with Unique Plurals**
From Latin, Greek, French, etc.; some have dual forms (traditional irregular vs. modern -s).
| Singular | Plural | Origin/Notes |
|--------------|-----------------|--------------|
| addendum | addenda | Latin; or addendums. |
| alumnus | alumni | Latin (male); alumnae (female). |
| analysis | analyses | Greek. |
| antenna | antennae | Latin (insects); antennas (tech). |
| appendix | appendices | Latin; or appendixes. |
| bacterium | bacteria | Greek. |
| basis | bases | Greek. |
| cactus | cacti | Latin/Greek; or cactuses. |
| corpus | corpora | Latin. |
| crisis | crises | Greek. |
| criterion | criteria | Greek. |
| curriculum | curricula | Latin; or curriculums. |
| datum | data | Latin; often singular now. |
| diagnosis | diagnoses | Greek. |
| fungus | fungi | Latin; or funguses. |
| hypothesis | hypotheses | Greek. |
| index | indices | Latin; or indexes. |
| medium | media | Latin; often singular now. |
| memorandum | memoranda | Latin; or memorandums. |
| oasis | oases | Greek. |
| parenthesis | parentheses | Greek. |
| phenomenon | phenomena | Greek. |
| radius | radii | Latin. |
| stimulus | stimuli | Latin. |
| syllabus | syllabi | Greek; or syllabuses. |
| synopsis | synopses | Greek. |
| thesis | theses | Greek. |
| vertex | vertices | Latin. |
### 7. **Other Miscellaneous Irregulars**
Unique cases or compounds.
| Singular | Plural | Notes |
|--------------|-----------------|-------|
| footman | footmen | -man compounds. |
| policeman | policemen | Now often "police officers." |
| fireman | firemen | Gender-neutral alternatives common. |
| thief | thieves | Vowel shift in some dialects. |
| loaf | loaves | -f to -ves. |
| leaf | leaves | -f to -ves. |
| life | lives | -f to -ves. |
| knife | knives | -fe to -ves. |
| wife | wives | -fe to -ves. |
| wolf | wolves | -f to -ves. |
| calf | calves | -f to -ves. |
| elf | elves | Mythical. |
| half | halves | -f to -ves. |
| hoof | hooves | Or "hoofs." |
| scarf | scarves | Or "scarfs." |
| wharf | wharves | Or "wharfs." |
### Additional Notes
- **-f/-fe to -ves Pattern**: This is semi-irregular (e.g., "knife → knives") but included for completeness, as it's a common exception.
- **Evolution and Usage**: Many foreign plurals (e.g., "octopus → octopi") are debated; "octopuses" is increasingly accepted. Always check context—modern English favors simplicity.
- **Sources**: This compilation draws from Wiktionary's appendix on irregular nouns and other grammar resources. For even more (e.g., obscure loanwords), consult the Oxford English Dictionary.

# 1) Vowel-mutation (ablaut) plurals
| Singular | Plural | IPA (sg) | IPA (pl) | Notes |
| ---------------------------- | -------- | ----------- | ----------- | ----------------------- |
| man | men | /mæn/ | /mɛn/ | vowel change |
| woman | women | /ˈwʊmən/ | /ˈwɪmɪn/ | vowel change |
| foot | feet | /fʊt/ | /fiːt/ | vowel change |
| goose | geese | /ɡuːs/ | /ɡiːs/ | vowel change |
| tooth | teeth | /tuːθ/ | /tiːθ/ | vowel change |
| mouse | mice | /maʊs/ | /maɪs/ | vowel change |
| louse | lice | /laʊs/ | /laɪs/ | vowel change |
| die *(gaming)* | dice | /daɪ/ | /daɪs/ | suppletive sense |
| ox *(see -en too)* | oxen | /ɒks/ | /ˈɒksən/ | archaic/marked alt. |
| brother | brethren | /ˈbrʌðə(r)/ | /ˈbrɛðrən/ | archaic sense “fellows” |
| cow | kine | /kaʊ/ | /kaɪn/ | archaic/regional |
| dormouse | dormice | /ˈdɔːˌmaʊs/ | /ˈdɔːˌmaɪs/ | vowel change |
| mouser *(rare “hunter cat”)* | mice | /ˈmaʊzə(r)/ | /maɪs/ | jocular/rare |
| alumnus *(Lat.)* | alumni | /əˈlʌmnəs/ | /əˈlʌmnaɪ/ | vowel change via Lat. |
| corpus *(Lat.)* | corpora | /ˈkɔːpəs/ | /ˈkɔːpərə/ | Lat. scientific |
| locus *(Lat.)* | loci | /ˈləʊkəs/ | /ˈləʊsaɪ/ | Lat. |
| genus *(Lat.)* | genera | /ˈdʒiːnəs/ | /ˈdʒɛnərə/ | Lat. |
| person *(see suppletive)* | people | /ˈpɜːsən/ | /ˈpiːpəl/ | suppletive |
*(The core ablaut set is mainly the first 8–10; others are included here to keep them together by “internal vowel change / historical pattern”.)*

## Bonus: Classical/scientific sets (quick reference)
| Class | Examples (sg→pl) | Notes |
| --------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------- |
| -um → -a | datum→data, bacterium→bacteria, medium→media | Lat. neuter |
| -us → -i | radius→radii, stimulus→stimuli, nucleus→nuclei | Lat. masc. (not bus→buses) |
| -a → -ae | alumna→alumnae, formula→formulae, vertebra→vertebrae | Lat. fem. |
| -ex/-ix → -ices | index→indices, appendix→appendices, matrix→matrices | scientific |
| -on → -a | phenomenon→phenomena, criterion→criteria | Greek neuter |
| -is → -es | crisis→crises, thesis→theses, analysis→analyses | Greek |
| zero plurals | fish, deer, moose, series, species, aircraft | context-driven |
| internal vowel change | man→men, goose→geese, foot→feet | Germanic |
| f/fe → ves | leaf→leaves, knife→knives, wolf→wolves | consonant shift |
---
## Notes on usage & style (helpful if you’re writing/editing)
* **Dual plurals**: Many words have both classical and Anglicized plurals (*cactus → cacti/cactuses*, *index → indices/indexes*). In **general writing**, the **-s** forms are widely accepted; in **technical fields**, the classical forms are still preferred.
* **Mass vs. count**: Some classical plurals now function as **mass nouns** (*graffiti, data, media*). Editors differ: treat **data** as plural in scientific style, but as a mass singular in many general contexts.
* **Zero plurals** for animals often indicate **collective** sense: *We caught three fish* (collective), but *three fishes* when emphasizing **species**.
* **Compounds**: In multi-word compounds, pluralize the **head noun** (*attorneys general*, *courts-martial*, *brothers-in-law*).
* **People vs. persons**: *People* is the usual plural of *person*; *persons* appears in legal/formal contexts or when counting individuals explicitly (e.g., **“maximum 8 persons”**).

Would you like me to show **how to use these plural-only nouns in sentences** (for example, “The scissors are sharp”)?
⭢ yes
Here are example sentences showing **how to correctly use plural-only nouns** in context 👇
---
### 🧍‍♀️ **1. Clothes**
* My **jeans are** too tight.
* These **shorts are** perfect for summer.
* His **pyjamas are** on the bed.
* Your **glasses are** on the table.
📝 *Notice:* We always use **are** or **were** (never *is* or *was*) because these nouns are plural.
---
### 🧰 **2. Tools and Instruments**
* The **scissors are** very sharp.
* Can you pass me the **pliers**?
* Those **tongs are** used for grilling.
* The **binoculars are** on the shelf.
---
### 🏡 **3. Places**
* The **Netherlands are** famous for their tulips.
* The **United States are** large and diverse. *(However, in modern English, people often say “The United States **is**…” treating it as a single country.)*
* The **Alps are** covered with snow in winter.
---
### 💼 **4. Academic or Abstract Nouns**
* **Politics are** often complicated. *(Though sometimes treated as singular: “Politics is a difficult subject.”)*
* **Economics is** my favourite subject. *(This one usually takes singular verbs.)*
* **Ethics are** important in business decisions.
📝 *These nouns look plural, but some (like “economics” and “mathematics”) are usually treated as **singular** depending on meaning.*
---
### 🎉 **5. Activities, Feelings, and Collections**
* My **belongings are** in that suitcase.
* The **surroundings are** peaceful and green.
* Our **earnings are** higher this year.
* The **outskirts are** far from the city centre.
* His **remains were** buried yesterday.
---
### 🎯 **6. Games**
* **Billiards is** a popular indoor game.
* **Darts is** played in many pubs.
* **Dominoes are** easy to learn.
---

"### Pluralia Tantum: English Nouns That Are Always Plural
In English, **pluralia tantum** (Latin for "plural only") are nouns that exist exclusively in the plural form, even when referring to a single item or concept. They don't have a singular counterpart (e.g., you can't say "a scissor" or "one jean"). These often include pairs of items, abstract concepts, or collective terms. Below is a categorized list of common examples, drawn from linguistic sources.
#### Tools and Utensils (Often Paired Items)
| Noun | Example Usage |
|---------------|--------------------------------|
| Scissors | "Pass me the scissors." |
| Pliers | "The pliers are rusty." |
| Tongs | "Use the tongs for grilling." |
| Tweezers | "These tweezers are precise." |
| Forceps | "The doctor used forceps." |
#### Clothing (Typically Worn as Pairs)
| Noun | Example Usage |
|---------------|--------------------------------|
| Jeans | "My jeans are too tight." |
| Trousers | "These trousers need hemming." |
| Pants | "I bought new pants." |
| Shorts | "Wear shorts in summer." |
| Pyjamas | "My pyjamas are comfortable." |
| Tights | "She wore black tights." |
#### Eyewear and Accessories
| Noun | Example Usage |
|---------------|--------------------------------|
| Glasses | "My glasses are fogging up." |
#### Abstract or Collective Concepts
| Noun | Example Usage |
|------------------|--------------------------------------|
| Belongings | "Pack your belongings." |
| Congratulations | "Send your congratulations." |
| Earnings | "Her earnings are impressive." |
| Goods | "The goods arrived on time." |
| Odds | "The odds are against us." |
| Outskirts | "We live on the outskirts." |
| Riches | "He inherited great riches." |
| Savings | "My savings are growing." |
| Surroundings | "Observe your surroundings." |
| Thanks | "Give my thanks to the host." |
#### Other Categories
- **Buildings/Spaces**: Premises, stairs.
- **General Items**: Clothes, suds.
These nouns take plural verbs (e.g., "The scissors are sharp") and are modified with "a pair of" for singular reference (e.g., "a pair of jeans"). Note that some can be regional (e.g., "pants" in American English vs. "trousers" in British). For a full linguistic deep dive, see resources on pluralia tantum."

name::
* McsEngl.EnglAdve'SynoMember,

generic-tree::
* SynoMembers-of-TermMebr,

adjective of EnglAdve

description::
* In most cases, an-adverb is-formed by adding -ly to an-adjective:
- cheap => cheaply
- quick => quickly

* If the-adjective ends in -y, replace the y with i and add -ly:
- easy => easily
- angry => angrily

* If the-adjective ends in -able, -ible, or -le, replace the -e with -y:
- probable => probably
- terrible => terribly
- gentle => gently

* If the-adjective ends in -ic, add -ally. Exception: public => publicly:
- basic => basically
- tragic => tragically
- economic => economically

* ome adverbs have the same form as the adjective: early, fast, hard, high, late, near, straight, wrong:
- It is a fast car. (adjective)
- He drives very fast. (adverb)

* Well is the-adverb that corresponds to the-adjective good,
- He is a good student.
- He studies well.
[https://www.ef.com/wwen/english-resources/english-grammar/forming-adverbs-adjectives/]

name::
* McsEngl.EnglAdve'adjective,

syntax of EnglAdve

description::
× Mcsh-creation: {2025-11-01},
"Sure — let’s go over the **syntax of English adverbs**, meaning how adverbs function and where they appear in sentences.
---
### 🧩 1. **What Adverbs Do**
Adverbs modify:
* **Verbs** → *She runs **quickly.***
* **Adjectives** → *It’s **very** cold.*
* **Other adverbs** → *He drives **quite** slowly.*
* **Whole sentences** → ***Unfortunately**, we missed the train.*
---
### ⚙️ 2. **Word Order (Syntax Rules)**
#### A. **Adverbs of Manner, Place, and Time**
Typical order after the main verb or object:
⭢ Subject + Verb + Object + Manner + Place + Time
**Example:**
⭢ She (subject) wrote (verb) the letter (object) neatly (manner) at home (place) yesterday (time).
⭢ ✅ Correct: *She wrote the letter neatly at home yesterday.*
⭢ ❌ Wrong: *She wrote neatly at home the letter yesterday.*
---
#### B. **Adverbs of Frequency**
(e.g. *always, usually, often, sometimes, rarely, never*)
They normally come **before the main verb**, but **after “be”**.
* Before main verb:
*She **always** eats breakfast.*
* After “be”:
*He is **usually** tired after work.*
---
#### C. **Adverbs of Degree**
(e.g. *very, quite, almost, too, enough*)
They usually come **before** the adjective or adverb they modify.
* *It’s **too** late.*
* *She runs **very** fast.*
* *He isn’t strong **enough**.*
---
#### D. **Sentence Adverbs**
(e.g. *fortunately, unfortunately, probably, clearly, honestly*)
They often appear **at the beginning** (or sometimes at the end) of a sentence.
* *Honestly, I don’t like it.*
* *Probably, she’ll call later.*
---
### 🧠 3. **Position Summary Table**
| Type of Adverb | Common Position | Example |
| Manner | after main verb/object | She sang beautifully. |
| Place | after verb/object | He looked everywhere. |
| Time | end of sentence | They arrived yesterday. |
| Frequency | before main verb / after “be” | She often travels. / He is always late. |
| Degree | before adjective/adverb | It’s quite cold. |
| Sentence | beginning or end | Luckily, we found it. |
---
### 🧱 4. **Multiple Adverbs**
When several adverbs appear together, the usual order is:
⭢ **Manner → Place → Time**
Example:
⭢ *She danced gracefully (manner) in the hall (place) last night (time).*
---
Would you like me to include a **short exercise** to practice adverb placement next?"
[{2025-11-01 retrieved} https://chatgpt.com/c/6905c2b9-fc08-832e-bd8e-2f1593712ba6]

The teacher that gives out candy is always the students’ favorite.

EnglVerbIdi.154-to-have-written

description::
· logo-infinitive.
===
"The perfect infinitive is most commonly found in type 3 conditional sentences as part of the conditional perfect, although it can be used in other places as well. The perfect infinitive is formed: to have + past participle
As with the present infinitive, there are situations where the zero form of the perfect infinitive is required, so the word to is omitted. This happens after most modal auxiliaries, and in other places where zero infinitives are used."
[https://www.ef.com/wwen/english-resources/english-grammar/perfect-infinitive/]
· _stxEngl: _stxTime:[(Before) I turn 40], I want to have written a book.

name::
* McsEngl.EnglVerbIdi.154-to-have-written,
* McsEngl.EnglVerbIdi.infinitive.perfect.to-have-written-154,
* McsEngl.EnglVerbIdi.to-have-written-154,
* McsEngl.to-have-written-154.EnglVerbIdi,

EnglVerbIdi.155-to-be-written

description::
· logo-infinitive.
"The passive infinitive is used in some constructions using the passive voice. It is particularly common after modal verbs (may, should, could, etc.) to indicate what is possible or what is correct. The passive infinitive is formed: to be + past participle
As with the present infinitive, there are situations where the zero form of the passive infinitive is required, so the word to is omitted. This happens after most modal auxiliaries, and in other places where zero infinitives are used."
[https://www.ef.com/wwen/english-resources/english-grammar/passive-infinitive/]
· _stxEngl: _stxSbj:[The carpet] _stxVrb:{needs} _stxObj:[to be washed].

name::
* McsEngl.EnglVerbIdi.155-to-be-written,
* McsEngl.EnglVerbIdi.infinitive.passive.to-be-written-155,
* McsEngl.EnglVerbIdi.infinitive.to-be-written-155,

EnglVerbIdi.158-to-have-been-writing

description::
· logo-infinitive.
"The perfect continuous infinitive is used to express a continuing but now completed action after a verb which must be followed by the infinitive. The perfect infinitive is formed:
to have been + present participle
As with the present infinitive, there are situations where the zero form of the perfect continuous infinitive is required, so the word to is omitted. This happens after most modal auxiliaries, and in other places where zero infinitives are used"
[https://www.ef.com/wwen/english-resources/english-grammar/perfect-continuous-infinitive/]
· _stxEngl: _stxSbj:[He] _stxVrb:{pretended} _stxObj:[to have been painting all day].

description::
"Must is used to express obligation, give orders and give advice. It can only be used for present and future reference. When the past is involved, you use have to.

- You must go to sleep now.
- You must get one of these new smoothie-makers – they’re great!
- She must be mad!"

EnglVerbIdi.180-should-have-written

EnglVerbIdi.193-ought-to-write

description::
"The crucial difference between should, ought to and must, is based on the extent to which they emphasize, in the sense that must is the most emphatic of the trio. On the other hand, ought to is less emphatic than must, but more than should. So, it is obvious that the degree of emphasis is least when we use should in our sentence."
[{2021-08-22 retrieved} https://keydifferences.com/difference-between-should-ought-to-and-must.html]

name::
* McsEngl.EnglVerbIdi.193-ought-to-write,
* McsEngl.EnglVerbIdi.ought-to-write-193,
* McsEngl.ought-to-write-193.EnglVerbIdi,

EnglVerbIdi.194-have-to-write

description::
"Have to mainly expresses general obligations, while must is used for specific obligations:
I have to brush my teeth twice a day.
I must tell you something.
Important: To express obligation, duty or necessity in the future or the past, must and need are not used. They are replaced by have to:
We must (need to) buy another ticket.
We had to buy another ticket yesterday.
We'll have to buy another ticket later."

name::
* McsEngl.EnglVerbIdi.194-have-to-write,
* McsEngl.EnglVerbIdi.have-to-write-194,
* McsEngl.have-to-write-194.EnglVerbIdi,

EnglVerbIdi.196-let's-write

description::
· denotes imperative first-person.

"Without the apostrophe, LETS is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb LET.
Use it in sentences where LETS can be replaced with either ALLOWS or PERMITS.
For example:
The key LETS you unlock the door.
The app LETS you meet new people."
[{2022-11-27 retrieved} https://www.sarahtownsendeditorial.co.uk/2019/02/lets-vs-lets-simple-tips-to-remember-the-difference/]

EnglVM.conditional-tense

description::
"The conditional tense—also sometimes referred to as the conditional mood—communicates what happens, will happen, might have happened, or would have happened if we do, will do, or did do something. The situation described can be real or imaginary; in either case, an action relies on something else (a condition)."
[{2022-12-04 retrieved} https://www.grammarbook.com/blog/definitions/clarifying-the-conditional-tense/]

name::
* McsEngl.conditional-moodEngl!⇒EnglVMCond,
* McsEngl.conditional-tenseEngl!⇒EnglVMCond,
* McsEngl.EnglVMCond,
* McsEngl.EnglVM.conditional-tense!⇒EnglVMCond,

EnglVMCond.zero

description::
· real.
· simple present + simple present.
"Zero conditional sentences express general truths—situations in which one thing always causes another. When you use a zero conditional, you’re talking about a general truth rather than a specific instance of something. Consider the following examples:
· _stxEngl: If you don’t brush your teeth, you get cavities.
· _stxEngl: When people smoke cigarettes, their health suffers.
There are a couple of things to take note of in the above sentences in which the zero conditional is used. First, when using the zero conditional, the correct tense to use in both clauses is the simple present tense. A common mistake is to use the simple future tense.
incorrect: When people smoke cigarettes, their health will suffer.
Secondly, notice that the words if and when can be used interchangeably in these zero conditional sentences. This is because the outcome will always be the same, so it doesn’t matter “if” or “when” it happens."
[{2022-12-05 retrieved} https://www.grammarly.com/blog/conditional-sentences/]

name::
* McsEngl.EnglVMCond.zero,

EnglVMCond.first

description::
· real, possible.
· simple present + simple future.
"First conditional sentences are used to express situations in which the outcome is likely (but not guaranteed) to happen in the future. Look at the examples below:
· _stxEngl: If you rest, you will feel better.
· _stxEngl: If you set your mind to a goal, you’ll eventually achieve it.
Note that we use the simple present tense in the if-clause and simple future tense in the main clause—that is, the clause that expresses the likely outcome. This is how we indicate that under a certain condition (as expressed in the if-clause), a specific result will likely happen in the future. Examine some of the common mistakes people make using the first conditional structure:
incorrect: If you will rest , you will feel better.
· _stxEngl: If you rest , you will feel better.
Explanation: Use the simple present tense in the if-clause.
incorrect: If you set your mind to a goal, you eventually achieve it.
· _stxEngl: If you set your mind to a goal, you’ll eventually achieve it.
Explanation: Use the zero conditional (i.e., simple present + simple present) only when a certain result is guaranteed. If the result is likely, use the first conditional (i.e., simple present + simple future)."
[{2022-12-05 retrieved} https://www.grammarly.com/blog/conditional-sentences/]

name::
* McsEngl.EnglVMCond.first,

EnglVMCond.second

description::
· unreal.
· simple past + could, should, would, might
"Second conditional sentences are useful for expressing outcomes that are completely unrealistic or will not likely happen in the future. Consider the examples below:
· _stxEngl: If I inherited a billion dollars, I would travel to the moon.
· _stxEngl: If I owned a zoo, I might let people interact with the animals more.
Notice the correct way to structure second conditional sentences is to use the simple past tense in the if-clause and an auxiliary modal verb (e.g., could, should, would, might) in the main clause (the one that expresses the unrealistic or unlikely outcome). The following sentences illustrate a couple of the common mistakes people make when using the second conditional:
incorrect: If I inherit a billion dollars, I would travel to the moon.
· _stxEngl: If I inherited a billion dollars, I would travel to the moon.
Explanation: When applying the second conditional, use the simple past tense in the if-clause.
incorrect: If I owned a zoo, I will let people interact with the animals more.
· _stxEngl: If I owned a zoo, I might let people interact with the animals more.
Explanation: Use a modal auxiliary verb in the main clause when using the second conditional mood to express the unlikelihood that the result will actually happen."
[{2022-12-05 retrieved} https://www.grammarly.com/blog/conditional-sentences/]

name::
* McsEngl.EnglVMCond.second,

EnglVMCond.third

description::
· unreal, hypothesis.
· past-perfect + would, could, should + have + past-participle
"Third conditional sentences are used to explain that present circumstances would be different if something different had happened in the past. Look at the following examples:
· _stxEngl: If you had told me you needed a ride, I would have left earlier.
· _stxEngl: If I had cleaned the house, I could have gone to the movies.
These sentences express a condition that was likely enough, but did not actually happen in the past. The speaker in the first sentence was capable of leaving early, but did not. Along these same lines, the speaker in the second sentence was capable of cleaning the house, but did not. These are all conditions that were likely, but regrettably did not happen.
Note that when using the third conditional, we use the past perfect (i.e., had + past participle) in the if-clause. The modal auxiliary (would, could, should, etc.) + have + past participle in the main clause expresses the theoretical situation that could have happened.
Consider these common mistakes when applying the third conditional:
incorrect: If you would have told me you needed a ride, I would have left earlier.
· _stxEngl: If you had told me you needed a ride, I would have left earlier.
Explanation: With third conditional sentences, do not use a modal auxiliary verb in the if-clause.
incorrect: If I had cleaned the house, I could go to the movies.
· _stxEngl: If I had cleaned the house, I could have gone to the movies.
Explanation: The third conditional mood expresses a situation that could have only happened in the past if a certain condition had been met. That’s why we use the modal auxiliary verb + have + the past participle."
[{2022-12-05 retrieved} https://www.grammarly.com/blog/conditional-sentences/]

name::
* McsEngl.EnglVMCond.third,

EnglVMCond.simple-future+simple-future

description::
· _stxEngl: If aspirin will ease my headache, I will take a couple tonight.
"when the action in the if-clause will take place after the action in the main clause."
[{2022-12-05 retrieved} https://www.grammarly.com/blog/conditional-sentences/]

name::
* McsEngl.EnglVMCond.simple-future+simple-future,

EnglVMCond.were-to

description::
· _stxEngl: If I were to be sick, I would miss another day of work.
· _stxEngl: If the rent were to have been a penny more, they would not have been able to pay it.
"when the likely or unlikely result is particularly awful or unthinkable."
[{2022-12-05 retrieved} https://www.grammarly.com/blog/conditional-sentences/]

name::
* McsEngl.EnglVMCond.were-to,

EnglVerbAuxi.can

description::
* EnglVerbIdi.161-can-write
* EnglVerbIdi.162-can-not-write
* EnglVerbIdi.163-can-(I)-write

"can has several uses:
* present ability: I can swim. The past tense is expressed by I could swim.
* present permission (in informal speech): You can go now. In the past tense one can use could (When I was a child, according to my parents' rules I could swim once a week).
* present moderate probability (seldom used): That can be true. There is no past form, since the more common that could be true conveys the same (present) tense."
[{2022-11-28 retrieved} https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tense%E2%80%93aspect%E2%80%93mood#Invariant_auxiliaries]

name::
* McsEngl.can-EnglVerbAuxi,
* McsEngl.EnglVerbAuxi.can,

EnglVerbAuxi.could

description::
* EnglVerbIdi.164-could-write
* EnglVerbIdi.165-could-(I)-write

"could is used in several ways:
* mild permission or advisability in the present: You could do that. The equivalent past form is could have + morphologically altered main verb (you could have done that).
* permission in the past: She said I could graduate in one more year.
* ability in the past: I could swim when I was five years old.
* slight probability in the present: That could be Mary at the door. The past tense equivalent is That could have been Mary at the door yesterday, with a morphologically altered main verb.
* conditional ability: I could do that if I knew how to swim. In the past one can say I could have done that if I had known how to swim.
* slight intention in the present: I could do that for you (and maybe I will). There is no past equivalent."
[{2022-11-28 retrieved} https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tense%E2%80%93aspect%E2%80%93mood#Invariant_auxiliaries]

name::
* McsEngl.could-EnglVerbAuxi,
* McsEngl.EnglVerbAuxi.could,

EnglVerbAuxi.may

description::
* EnglVerbIdi.167-may-write
* EnglVerbIdi.168-may-not-write
* EnglVerbIdi.169-may-(I)-write

* possibility,
* permission,

"may can indicate either the mode of possibility or that of permission:
* possibility in the present or future: He may be there already, He may arrive tomorrow. The form "He may have arrived," with a morphological change to the main verb, indicates not just the mode of possibility but also the aspectual feature of viewing a past event from a present viewpoint. This form applies only to this possibility usage.
* permission in the present or future: You may go now / next week. There is no corresponding way to indicate the presence of permission in the past."
[{2022-11-28 retrieved} https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tense%E2%80%93aspect%E2%80%93mood#Invariant_auxiliaries]

* EnglVerbIdi.172-might-not-write

* advisability,
* possibility,

"might conveys slight likelihood in the present or future (He might be there already, he might arrive tomorrow). It can also convey slight advisability (You might try that). The past can be substituted using the form might have + morphologically altered main verb."
[{2022-11-28 retrieved} https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tense%E2%80%93aspect%E2%80%93mood#Invariant_auxiliaries]

EnglVerbAuxi.ought-to

description::
"ought to + verb can mean the same thing as either of the last two mentioned uses of should: mild obligatory mode in present or future (He ought to do that now / next week) or probabilistic mode in the present or future (This approach ought to work). The past tense form ought to have done that, ought to have worked, with a morphological change to the main verb, conveys the same information as the corresponding should have form in both cases."
[{2022-11-28 retrieved} https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tense%E2%80%93aspect%E2%80%93mood#Invariant_auxiliaries]

name::

description::
* EnglVerbIdi.175-shall-write
* EnglVerbIdi.176-shall-not-write
* EnglVerbIdi.177-shall-(I)-write

"shall indicates futurity or intention in the first person (I shall go); for the other persons, it indicates obligation, often negative as in you shall not lie, but this usage is old-fashioned."
[{2022-11-28 retrieved} https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tense%E2%80%93aspect%E2%80%93mood#Invariant_auxiliaries]

EnglVerbAuxi.should

description::
* EnglVerbIdi.178-should-write
* EnglVerbIdi.179-should-not-write
* EnglVerbIdi.180-should-have-written
* EnglVerbIdi.181-should-not-have-written
* EnglVerbIdi.182-should-(I)-write
* EnglVerbIdi.183-should-not-(I)-write

"should has several uses:
* present or future tense combined with possibility mode: If he should be here already, ...; If he should arrive tomorrow, ...
* mild obligatory mode in the present or future tense: He should do that now / next week. The past tense can be substituted by using the form He should have done that, with a morphological change to the main verb.
* probabilistic mode in the present or future tense: This approach should work. The corresponding past tense form should have worked implies impersonal obligation rather than probability."
[{2022-11-28 retrieved} https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tense%E2%80%93aspect%E2%80%93mood#Invariant_auxiliaries]

name::
* McsEngl.should-EnglVerbAuxi,
* McsEngl.EnglVerbAuxi.should,

EnglVerbAuxi.used-to

description::
"used to indicates both past tense and habitual aspect ("I used to run every day.") or occasionally stative aspect ("The sun used to shine more brightly"). It cannot be used with the very recent past (*I used to run every day last week is not acceptable, but I used to run every day last summer is acceptable though usually no lexical time marker like last summer is included). The form that negates the main verb is used not to + verb (or used to not + verb); the form that negates habituality is did not use to + verb."
[{2022-11-28 retrieved} https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tense%E2%80%93aspect%E2%80%93mood#Invariant_auxiliaries]

name::
* McsEngl.EnglVerbAuxi.used-to,
* McsEngl.used-to-EnglVerbAuxi,

EnglVerbAuxi.will

description::
* EnglVerbIdi.121-will-write
* EnglVerbIdi.122-will-not-write
* EnglVerbIdi.123-will-(I)-write
* EnglVerbIdi.124-will-(I)-not-write
* EnglVerbIdi.125-will-have-written
* EnglVerbIdi.126-will-not-have-written
* EnglVerbIdi.127-will-(I)-have-written
* EnglVerbIdi.128-will-(I)-not-have-written
* EnglVerbIdi.129-will-be-written
* EnglVerbIdi.130-will-not-be-written
* EnglVerbIdi.131-will-(I)-be-written
* EnglVerbIdi.132-will-(I)-not-be-written
* EnglVerbIdi.133-will-have-been-written
* EnglVerbIdi.134-will-not-have-been-written
* EnglVerbIdi.135-will-(I)-have-been-written
* EnglVerbIdi.136-will-(I)-not-have-been-written
* EnglVerbIdi.137-will-be-writing
* EnglVerbIdi.138-will-not-be-writing
* EnglVerbIdi.139-will-(I)-be-writing
* EnglVerbIdi.140-will-(I)-not-be-writing
* EnglVerbIdi.141-will-have-been-writing
* EnglVerbIdi.142-will-not-have-been-writing
* EnglVerbIdi.143-will-(I)-have-been-writing
* EnglVerbIdi.144-will-(I)-not-have-been-writing
* EnglVerbIdi.145-will-being-written
* EnglVerbIdi.146-will-not-being-written
* EnglVerbIdi.147-will-(I)-being-written
* EnglVerbIdi.148-will-(I)-not-being-written
* EnglVerbIdi.149-will-have-being-written
* EnglVerbIdi.150-will-not-have-being-written
* EnglVerbIdi.151-will-(I)-have-being-written
* EnglVerbIdi.152-will-(I)-not-have-being-written

"will has a number of different uses involving tense, aspect, and modality:
* It can express aspect alone, without implying futurity: In "He will make mistakes, won't he?", the reference is to a tendency in the past, present, and future and as such expresses habitual aspect.
* It can express either of two types of modality alone, again without implying futurity: In "That will be John at the door", there is an implication of present time and probabilistic mode, while "You will do it right now" implies obligatory mode.
* It can express both intentional modality and futurity, as in "I will do it."
* It can express futurity without modality: "The sun will die in a few billion years."
As with would, the negative form will not negates the main verb but in the intentional mode may also indicate negative intentionality.
In each case the time of viewpoint can be placed in the past by replacing will with would."
[{2022-11-28 retrieved} https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tense%E2%80%93aspect%E2%80%93mood#Invariant_auxiliaries]

name::
* McsEngl.will-EnglVerbAuxi,
* McsEngl.EnglVerbAuxi.will,

EnglVerbAuxi.would

description::
* EnglVerbIdi.184-would-not-write
* EnglVerbIdi.184-would-write
* EnglVerbIdi.185-would-(I)-write
* EnglVerbIdi.186-would-be-writing
* EnglVerbIdi.187-would-have-been-writing
* EnglVerbIdi.188-would-have-written
* EnglVerbIdi.189-would-be-written
* EnglVerbIdi.190-would-not-be-written

"would has three alternative uses:
* past tense combined with habitual aspect ("Last summer I would run every day.")
* conditional mood for a present or future action (If I could, I would do it now / next week). In the first person, intentional modality may also be present.
* past tense, prospective aspect for an action occurring after the past-tense viewpoint ("After I graduated in 1990, I would work in industry for the next ten years.")
The negative form would not + verb negates the main verb, but in the conditional and intentional mood in the first person the intentional modality may also be negated to indicate negative intention."
[{2022-11-27 retrieved} https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tense%E2%80%93aspect%E2%80%93mood]

name::
* McsEngl.would-EnglVerbAuxi,
* McsEngl.EnglVerbAuxi.would,

semo-relation of EnglVerb

description::
· there-is-no one to one mapping between lago-verb and verb.
· for the-576 realis lago-verb-members correspond 152 atomic-verb-members.
· the-subject help us to find the-mapping.

* ends in 2 consonants: climb;climb-s;climb-ed;climb-ing;climb-ed,

EnglVerb.A2:stop-stops-stopped-stopping-stopped

description::
· englverbA2 creates its auxiliaryNo-parts by adding a-suffix on atomicNo-verb:
· stop, stop-s, stop-ped, stop-ping, stop-ped.
">English verbs that double their final consonant:
Perfect 👍 — here’s a **clear visual summary table** of when to **double or not double** the final consonant in English verbs before adding a vowel suffix (*-ing, -ed, -er, etc.*).
---
## 🧩 **Consonant Doubling Rules Summary**
| **Pattern** | **Double Final Consonant?** | **Examples (✅ Correct)** | **Notes** |
| 🔹 One syllable, ends with *vowel + consonant* | ✅ **Yes** | stop → stopping / stopped
plan → planning / planned
hop → hopping / hopped | Short vowel + single consonant pattern |
| 🔹 Two syllables, **stress on final syllable** | ✅ **Yes** | prefer → preferred / preferring
occur → occurred / occurring
admit → admitted / admitting | Stress is key! |
| 🔹 Two syllables, **stress not on final syllable** | ❌ **No** | open → opening / opened
happen → happening / happened
offer → offering / offered | Stress on first syllable = no doubling |
| 🔹 Ends with **two consonants** | ❌ **No** | start → starting / started
help → helping / helped | Already two consonants |
| 🔹 Ends with **long vowel + consonant** | ❌ **No** | hope → hoping / hoped
keep → keeping / kept
wait → waiting / waited | Only short vowels double |
| 🔹 Ends with **w, x, or y** | ❌ **No** | show → showing
mix → mixing
play → playing | Never doubled |
| 🔹 British English (unstressed 2-syllable verbs) | ✅ **Yes (UK)** / ❌ **No (US)** | travel → travelling 🇬🇧 / traveling 🇺🇸
cancel → cancelling 🇬🇧 / canceling 🇺🇸 | Regional difference |
| 🔹 Irregular verbs (exceptions) | ⚠️ **Mixed** | run → running
swim → swimming
get → getting
begin → beginning | Follow stress + irregular vowel changes |
---

EnglVerb.modal

description::
"Here's a list of the modal verbs in English:
can could may might will would must shall should ought to
Modals are different from normal verbs:
1: They don't use an 's' for the third person singular.
2: They make questions by inversion ('she can go' becomes 'can she go?').
3: They are followed directly by the infinitive of another verb (without 'to').
[{2021-08-08 retrieved} https://www.perfect-english-grammar.com/modal-verbs.html]
===
"A modal verb is a type of verb that is used to indicate modality – that is: likelihood, ability, permission, request, capacity, suggestions, order, obligation, or advice. Modal verbs always accompany the base (infinitive) form of another verb having semantic content.[1] In English, the modal verbs commonly used are can, could, may, might, shall, should, will, would, and must."
[{2021-08-08 retrieved} https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modal_verb]

name::
* McsEngl.modal-EnglVerb,
* McsEngl.EnglVerb.modal,

EnglConj.at

description::
× senso-mind-relation: rlnSpace,
- space-point.
- with specific locations, addresses, companies, stores, events, parties, desks, counters.
· _stxEngl: _stxSbj:[My brother the research associate] _stxVrb:{works} _stxSpace:[(at) a large polling firm].
· _stxEngl: [There] (aren't) [any sea animals] _stxSpace:[(at) the zoo].
· _stxEngl: _stxSbj:[They] _stxVrb:{will meet} _stxObj:[us] _stxSpace:[(at) [[the newest cafe] [(in) the market]]].

× senso-mind-relation: rlnSpace-direction.towards,
· _stxEngl: _stxSbj:[She] _stxVrb:{looked} _stxDirection:[(at) the papers] _stxSpace:[(around) her]. [HarperCollins]
· _stxEngl: [The crowds (became) violent] [(and) [(threw) [petrol bombs] [(at) the police]]]. [HarperCollins]

× senso-mind-relation: rlnTime,
· _stxEngl: _stxSbj=[We] _stxVrb:{began} _stxObj:[working] _stxTime:[(at) dawn].

EnglConj.in

description::
× senso-mind-relation: rlnSpace.in,
- with enclosed spaces, buildings, organizations, regions, water, deserts, mountain ranges, forests, cities, countries, continents, the sky, space, cars, groups of people, little boats.
· _stxEngl: _stxSbj:[They] _stxVrb:{will meet} _stxObj:[us] _stxSpace:[(at) [[the newest cafe] [(in) the market]]].

× senso-mind-relation: rlnSpace-direction.into,

× senso-mind-relation: rlnTime,
* with months: in July,
* with years: in 1959,
* with seasons: in summer,
* with centuries: in the 20th century,
* with parts of day with "the": in the night,
· _stxEngl: _stxSbj:[Pat] _stxVrb:{drinks} _stxObj:[(both) [coffee in the morning] (and) [tea in the afternoon]].

× senso-mind-relation: rlnBelief-of-entity,

× senso-mind-relation: rlnManner,

verb-argument of EnglLogoView

description::
× McsHitp-creation: {2025-02-07},
× generic: verb-argument,

"Okay, let's break down "English verb-argument structure." This is a core concept in linguistics, specifically in syntax and semantics. Here's a comprehensive explanation, covering the key aspects:

**1. What is an Argument?**
* In linguistics, an "argument" is a *required* phrase or element that completes the meaning of a verb. Think of it as the participants in the action or state described by the verb. They are grammatically *licensed* by the verb.
* Arguments are *not* the same as adjuncts. Adjuncts are optional modifiers that add extra information (time, place, manner, etc.) but aren't essential to the verb's core meaning.

**2. Key Types of Arguments (Roles)**
Here are the most common types of arguments, along with their typical semantic roles:
* **Subject (S):** Usually performs the action (agent) or is in the state described by the verb. In English, the subject typically comes *before* the verb in declarative sentences.
* Example: **The cat** (S) chased the mouse. (**The cat** is the agent, performing the action of chasing).
* Example: **The door** (S) is open. (**The door** is in the state of being open).
* **Direct Object (DO):** Typically the entity that is directly affected by the action of the verb. It often undergoes a change or is the "patient" of the action.
* Example: The cat chased **the mouse** (DO). (**The mouse** is the patient, being chased).
* Example: She ate **the apple** (DO). (**The apple** undergoes a change - being eaten).
* **Indirect Object (IO):** Typically the recipient or beneficiary of the action. Often indicates *to whom* or *for whom* something is done. In English, the indirect object often appears with the prepositions "to" or "for," but can also appear without them (in a "dative shift" construction).
* Example: He gave **her** (IO) a book (DO). (**Her** is the recipient).
* Example: He gave a book (DO) **to her** (IO). (Same meaning, different structure).
* Example: She baked **him** (IO) a cake (DO). (Dative shift – no preposition).
* Example: She baked a cake (DO) **for him** (IO).
* **Oblique Argument:** An argument that is marked by a preposition. The preposition is *selected* by the verb – it's not just any preposition. This is crucial.
* Example: He relies **on his friends**. ("On" is required by "rely").
* Example: She put the book **on the table**. ("On" is selected by "put," though "the table" could also be analyzed as a locative adjunct in some frameworks).
* Example: They argued **about the problem**. ("About" is selected by "argued").
* **Predicate Complement** (also called a predicative complement): Completes the meaning of a *copular* verb (like "be," "seem," "become," "appear," etc.). It describes or renames the subject. There are two main types:
* **Subject Complement:** A noun phrase or adjective phrase that provides information regarding the subject.
* Example: He is **a doctor**. ("a doctor" renames "he").
* Example: The sky became **dark**. ("dark" describes "the sky").
* Example: She seems **happy**.("happy" describes "she).
* **Object Complement:** A noun phrase or adjective phrase that provides information about the direct object (less common).
* Example: They elected him **president**.("president" renames him)
* Example: The news made her **sad**.(sad describes her)

**3. Verb Valency (Argument Structure)**
* **Valency** refers to the *number* and *type* of arguments a verb requires. This is a fundamental property of each verb. Think of it as the verb's "argument recipe."
* Here's a breakdown by valency:
* **Intransitive Verbs (Valency = 1):** Take only a subject.
* Example: She *sleeps*.
* Example: The baby *cried*.
* **Transitive Verbs (Valency = 2):** Take a subject and a direct object.
* Example: He *kicked* the ball.
* Example: She *reads* books.
* **Ditransitive Verbs (Valency = 3):** Take a subject, a direct object, and an indirect object.
* Example: He *gave* her a flower.
* Example: She *told* him a story.
* **Complex-Transitive Verbs** Take a subject, a direct object, and either an object complement or an obligatory adverbial.
* Example: We *elected* him president.
* Example: I *consider* him a friend.
* Example: I *put* the book on the table.
* **Copular Verbs:** Take a subject and subject complement.
* Example: He *is* tall.
* Example: They *became* friends.
* **Zero-place Predicates** (Rare): Some verbs, often related to weather, have no arguments at all.
* Example: *It* is raining. ("It" here is a dummy subject, not a true argument).

**4. How to Identify Arguments**
Here are some key tests to distinguish arguments from adjuncts:
* **Obligatoriness:** Arguments are *required* by the verb. If you remove an argument, the sentence becomes ungrammatical or changes meaning significantly. Adjuncts are optional.
* Example: "He gave her a book." If you remove "her" or "a book," the sentence is ungrammatical (*He gave a book, *He gave her). But, "He gave her a book yesterday" - removing "yesterday" is fine.
* **Verb Selection:** The specific verb dictates which prepositions (if any) are used with its oblique arguments. This is *lexical selection*.
* Example: "rely on," "depend on," "account for," "listen to" – the prepositions are fixed by the verb.
* **Iteration:** You can usually add multiple adjuncts, but you can't typically repeat arguments (without coordination).
* Example: "He walked quickly *in the park* *yesterday* *with his dog*" (multiple adjuncts).
* You can't say: *"He gave her a book a pen"* (without "and" – "He gave her a book and a pen").
* **Do-So Test** The phrase "do so" can replace a verb phrase, including its arguments, but not adjuncts.
* Example: John ate the cake, and Mary did so, too. (Did so = ate the cake)
* Example: *John ate the cake slowly, and Mary did so quickly. (This doesn't work the same way. Did so = ate the cake.)
* **Fronting and Clefting:** These tests often highlight adjuncts.

**5. Examples with Different Verb Types**
Let's look at some more examples, categorized by verb type:
* **Intransitive:**
* The bird *sang*. (S)
* The flowers *bloomed*. (S)
* **Transitive:**
* She *painted* the picture. (S, DO)
* He *built* a house. (S, DO)
* **Ditransitive:**
* They *sent* him a letter. (S, IO, DO)
* She *offered* me some advice. (S, IO, DO)
* **Copular:**
* The cat *is* fluffy. (S, Subject Complement)
* He *seems* tired. (S, Subject Complement)
* **Complex-Transitive**
* They made him *king*. (S, DO, Object Complement)
* I put the book *on the desk*. (S, DO, Obligatory Adverbial)
* **Verbs with Oblique Arguments:**
* She *depends* on her sister. (S, Oblique)
* They *argued* about politics. (S, Oblique)
* He *looked* at the painting. (S, Oblique. "at the painting" can be interpreted as a directional adjunct too, depends on theoretical framework)

**6. Why is Argument Structure Important?**
Understanding verb-argument structure is crucial for:
* **Parsing Sentences:** Correctly identifying the grammatical relationships between words.
* **Semantic Interpretation:** Understanding the meaning of sentences, including who did what to whom.
* **Machine Translation:** Teaching computers to understand and translate languages.
* **Natural Language Processing (NLP):** Developing computer systems that can process and understand human language.
* **Language Acquisition:** Understanding how children learn to use verbs and their arguments.
* **Theoretical Linguistics:** Developing theories of grammar and how language works.

**7. Beyond the Basics (Advanced Concepts)**
* **Thematic Roles (Theta Roles):** These are semantic roles assigned to arguments (Agent, Patient, Theme, Goal, Source, Instrument, Experiencer, etc.). They describe the role an argument plays in the event. Different theories have slightly different sets of theta roles.
* **Argument Structure Alternations:** Some verbs can appear in different argument structures, often with subtle meaning changes. Examples:
* **Dative Alternation:** "He gave her the book" vs. "He gave the book to her."
* **Causative Alternation:** "The window broke" vs. "He broke the window."
* **Middle Voice:** "The bread cuts easily" (the subject is the patient, but the verb is active).
* **Unaccusative vs. Unergative Verbs (Intransitive Verbs):** This is a distinction within intransitive verbs.
* **Unaccusative verbs:** The subject is *semantically* like a direct object (it undergoes the action). Example: "The vase *fell*."
* **Unergative verbs:** The subject is a true agent. Example: "She *danced*."
* **Light Verbs:** Verbs like "take," "give," "have," "make" that combine with a noun to form a complex predicate (e.g., "take a walk," "give a hug," "have a look," "make a decision").
* **Resultative Constructions:** These involve adding a phrase that describes the *result* of the action. Example: "He hammered the metal *flat*." ("flat" describes the result of the hammering).
* **Different Frameworks**: Different linguistic theories (e.g. Generative Grammar, Construction Grammar, Head-Driven Phrase Structure Grammar (HPSG), Lexical Functional Grammar (LFG)) have different ways of representing and explaining argument structure, but the core concepts remain largely the same.
This comprehensive explanation should provide a solid understanding of English verb-argument structure. Remember to consult linguistic resources and specific grammars for deeper dives into particular aspects."
[{2025-02-07 retrieved} https://gemini.google.com/app/103a88b88ab4e596]

· like Koine-Greek, lagSpchEngl is-changing rapidly.
· in my opinion, its vowels will-be the-five most distinguishable of modern Spanish, Italian, Greek /a e i o u/.

relation-lagSpchEngl-to-lagAlfaEngl

description::
"In generic, the English language, being the product of many other languages and having only been codified orthographically in the 16th century, has fewer consistent relationships between sounds and letters than many other languages. The consequence of this orthographic history is that reading can be challenging. It takes longer for students to become completely fluent readers of English than of many other languages, including French, Greek, and Spanish".
[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/English_language, {2008-04-14}]
